{{Infobox royalty
|name = Dmitri Ivanovich
|title = [[Tsesarevich|Tsesarevich of Russia]]
|house-type = Dynasty
|house = [[Rurik dynasty|Rurik]]
|father = [[Ivan the Terrible|Ivan IV of Russia]]
|mother = [[Anastasia Romanovna]]
|birth_date = 11 October 1552
|birth_place = [[Moscow Kremlin]], [[Moscow]]
|death_date = {{death date|1553|6|26|df=y}} (aged {{age for infant|1552|10|11|1553|6|26}})
|death_place = Sora River, Northern [[Russia]]
|burial_place = [[Archangel Cathedral]], Moscow
}}
'''Dmitri Ivanovich''' ({{lang-ru|Дмитрий Иванович}}; 11 October 1552{{spaced ndash}}26 June 1553) was the first [[Tsarevich]] or [[Tsesarevich]] - the [[heir apparent]] - of the [[Tsardom of Russia]], as the eldest son of [[Ivan the Terrible]], or ''Ivan IV of Russia'' and his first [[Tsaritsa]], [[Anastasia Romanovna]]. He was the third child and first son of the couple and died in infancy.

==Birth==
Ivan became [[Grand Prince of Moscow]] at the age of three, in 1533. At his coronation, on 16 January 1547, the sixteen-year-old Ivan resurrected the title of [[Tsar]], occasionally used by his grandfather and namesake, [[Ivan III of Moscow]]. Holding all of the power in his empire, he could choose his bride. He eventually picked [[Anastasia Romanovna]], the daughter of a wealthy [[boyar]]. Throughout the first four years of their marriage, Anastasia presented Ivan with two daughters, Anna and Maria. Both died in infancy, Anna at the age of eleven months and Maria before her sixth month.<ref name="gene">{{cite web | url=http://genealogy.euweb.cz/russia/rurik15.html | title=Rurikid Genealogy 15 | publisher=genealogy.euweb.cz | accessdate=January 8, 2012 | author=Marek, Miroslav}}{{Self-published source|date=August 2012}}{{Better source|date=August 2012}}</ref> However, on 11 October 1552,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hrono.ru/geneal/ryuriki/geanl_rk_39.php | title=Московские Великие князья (''Grand Dukes of Russia'') | publisher=Hrono | work=''Хpohoc'' (Chronos) | date=January 20, 2000 | accessdate=January 8, 2012 | author=Rumyantsev, Vyacheslav}}</ref> Anastasia gave birth to a son, whom they named Dmitri, presumably after ancestor [[Dmitri Donskoy]]. During a severe illness, Ivan asked the boyars to take an oath, making his infant son his [[heir apparent]] and the first [[Tsesarevich]].<ref name="ar">{{cite web | url=http://aminpro.narod.ru/kreml_G_0021.html | title=Анастасия Романовна и Иван Грозный (''Anastasia Romanovna and Ivan the Terrible'') | publisher=amnipro.narod.ru | accessdate=January 8, 2012 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111113153335/http://aminpro.narod.ru/kreml_G_0021.html | archivedate=November 13, 2011 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref> However, the boyars were not very happy about this, as they wanted to see Ivan's cousin, [[Vladimir of Staritsa]], succeed<ref name="ar" /> but they reluctantly accepted.<ref name="ar" /> Historians cannot agree whether this episode occurred in 1552<ref name="ar" /> or 1553.<ref name="aac">{{cite web | url=http://www.peoples.ru/state/king/russia/ivan_iiv_grozniy/ | title=Ivan IV Groznîi | publisher=peoples.ru | accessdate=January 8, 2012}}</ref>

==Death==
In the summer of 1553, Ivan proposed a [[pilgrim]]age to [[Kirillo-Belozersky Monastery]], near the present-day village of [[Kirillov (town)|Kirillov]]. While on the Sora River, the royal boat was hit by a wave, it overturned<ref name="ar" /> and the Tsesarevich was dropped by his [[wet nurse]].<ref name="aac" /> The adults managed to escape, but by the time they got to the baby, Dmitri had drowned.<ref name="ar" /> "The Chronicle" records that [[Maximus the Greek]], who had recently visited Ivan, foresaw the death of the Tsesarevich.<ref name="ak">{{cite web | url=http://www.sedmitza.ru/text/438701.html | title=Chapter III: Returning to Moscow | publisher=sedmitza.ru | accessdate=January 8, 2012 | author=[[Andrey Kurbsky|Kurbsky, Andrey]]}}</ref> According to [[Andrey Kurbsky]], Maximus had told Ivan that "''he should not go such a long way with his wife and newborn lad''".<ref name="ak" />

==Aftermath==
Dmitri was interred in the [[Archangel Cathedral]]. After his death, Anastasia would have three more children, two of whom would survive infancy. Ivan's youngest son by his last wife was named [[Tsarevich Dmitry Ivanovich of Russia (born 1582)|Dmitry]] after his eldest son who had died more than thirty years before.

